                                    =============
                                    IOC container
                                    =============

=> IOC stands for inversion of Control.
=> IoC is responsible for Dependeny Injection in Spring Application.
=> Dependency Injection means creating and injecting dependent bean objects into target bean classes.

Note: IoC container will manage life cycle of Spring Beans.

Note: We need to provide "Java classes + Bean Configuration" as input for IOC then
      IOC will perform DI and provides Spring Beans which are ready to use.

=====================
What is Spring Bean ?
======================
      => Spring bean and bean , both are same.
      =>  Any java class whose life cycle (creation to distruction )is managed by IOC is called spring bean.
      => We can represent Java class as Spring Bean in 2 ways
       1. XML Approach
         ex: <bean id ="id1" class = "pkg.ClassNmae " />
       2. Annotation Approach( Recommended)
         ex: @Component, @Service, @Repository etc.... 

Note: Spring supports both approaches but SpringBoot only supports Annotation approach.(no xmls).

                              Java classes
                                    |
                                    |
   Bean configuration ------- IOC container(perform the DI(Dependecy Injection))   ---------------> Spring Beans (Ready to use )

============================
How to start IOC in Spring ?
============================

1. BeanFactory
2.ApplicationContext(recommended)


  Ex: ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext(String configFile);

 Note: Bean configuration file contains Bean defination. 

     (target class, dependency injection types, dependent class)

Note: When IoC container started it will read bean defination from bean configuration File and it will perform Dependency Injection.



=========================================================
First Application Development by using Spring core Module
==========================================================

Pre requesites: JDK1.8v, STS IDE
--------------------------------

1.Create Maven project in IDE
2. Add Spring core dependencies in pom.xml file(www.mvnrepository.com)

      <dependency>
          <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
          <artifactId>spring-context</artifactId>
          <version>5.2.22.RELEASE</version>
      </dependency>

3.Create required Java classes (Ex: IEngine, PetrolEngine, DieselEngine, and Car)
4.Create Bean configuration File and configure Bean Definations.

    <bean id ="petrolEng" class="in.ashokit.beans.PetrolEngine"/>
    <bean id ="dieselEng" class="in.ashokit.beans.DieselEngine"/>
    <bean id ="car" class="in.ashokit.beans.Car"/>
       <property name ="eng " ref = "petrolEng" />
    
     </bean>

Note: Here "property" tag used for setter injection.


5. Create Main Class and start IOC container to test the application.

Main.java
=========

package in.ashokit.main;

import org.springframework.context.*;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationCotext;

import in.ashokit.beans.Car;
public class App {

	
	 public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		 //staring IOC container
		 ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationCotext("Beans.xml");
		 
		 //getting bean object from IOC

		 Car car = context.getBean(car.getClass());
		 car.drive();
	}
}








